const char gCompressedText_MSG_0CEF[] = "	)	Master Knoll...\x03I know you... You'reNatasha, from the temple.\x03	Yes. I remember seeing youmany times back in Grado.\x03But this is the first timewe've ever actually spoken.\x03I don't know what it is, but clerics andmages seem to be like oil and water.\x03And we mages can be an enigmatic bunchat times. Shadowy and sinister...\x03Or at least, that's how I've alwaysimagined you clerics saw us.\x03	Oh, no! I never--\x03Well, no. You're right. We had fewdealings with the mages.\x03But that's in the past. I havea question for you, Master Knoll.\x03I think I can guess. It's about theSacred Stones and Prince Lyon, is it?\x03	It is.\x03My mentor died...trying to warn us aboutthe threat our Sacred Stone posed.\x03I want to know the truth.\x03What is Emperor Vigarde up to? Whatis Prince Lyon's role in this?\x03There are as many truths out thereas there are people to tell them.\x03Perhaps it's best simply to choose thetruth with which you are most comfortable.\x03	......\x03In the eyes of your mentor, I wouldimagine we must have seemed quite evil.\x03He imagined our magical studies usingthe Sacred Stone were sacrilege.\x03I suspect he quite loathed theancient magics he called dark.\x03	You're wrong...\x03	\nMy mentor wasn't like that at all!\x03And isn't this war the direct resultof all your dark magic research?\x03......\x03\n......\x03Hm... Well, I supposeyou are right about that.\x03Your magic stems from faith in theunknowable, the divine presence.\x03In contrast, dark magic stems fromknowledge, from understanding.\x03We distrust what we do not understand,and we strive to know the unknowable.\x03Perhaps our disciplines trulyare incompatible.\x03\n......\x03";
const char gCompressedText_MSG_0CF0[] = "	)...Our researches ended inmiserable failure.\x03Grado's Sacred Stone was shattered.Prince Lyon, corrupted...\x03And this whole tragedy that unfoldsaround us even now.\x03It's true. We mages have triggeredthis age's greatest calamity.\x03	But why? What was it all for?\x03What did you hope to accomplishwith the power of the Sacred Stone?\x03All Prince Lyon wanted was to helppeople...and we are his servants.\x03	Help people?\x03We read of a spell entitled the time shear.It causes, in effect, a hole in time.\x03This spell warps time, punches ahole through cause and effect.\x03	......\x03We lack the knowledge to reproducethis ancient spell today.\x03Prince Lyon, however, was convincedthat we could unravel its secret.\x03He felt we could use it to predict--and even prevent--future events.\x03	...Prevent...the future?\x03Oh, we dedicated years to studyingthis spell.\x03You see, the greater the disaster, thefarther it sends ripples through time.\x03We learned to read these ripples fromthe future, hoping to save lives.\x03If we could know when a disaster wouldstrike, we could evacuate people.\x03We could save millions of lives.\x03	But...\x03It seems so, so blasphemous.\x03That worldly creatures shouldtake control of fate, it--\x03Are you saying that, knowing thefuture, we should do nothing?\x03We should simply allow people todie in order to preserve fate?\x03	I...\x03I'm sorry. I don't mean tosound hostile.\x03Prince Lyon himself was troubledby these same doubts, you see.\x03But we pressed on with our studies.\x03We felt it was our duty, in theinterest of all Grado's people.\x03	......\x03Perhaps we were bitter that wereceive no credit for aiding Grado.\x03That we receive no accolades for ourresearch, for the benefit it brings.\x03I do not know. But we pressed on,nonetheless.\x03The misconceptions linking the ancientmagics to evil die hard and slow.\x03Prince Lyon sought to change that.\x03He wanted, as we all wanted, toprove that our magic had good uses.\x03	Prince Lyon would never--\x03With our aid, Prince Lyon predicteda great storm rising in the south.\x03He barred ships from leaving port,and, oh, how the people complained.\x03But the storm came, and the seasraged. We saved countless lives.\x03And Prince Lyon cared not at allif the people loved him for it.\x03He only wanted them to be safe.\x03	......\x03And now, I see it all so clearly.All our research amounts to nothing.\x03All I can do now is lament ourhunger for knowledge. Our greed.\x03";
const char gCompressedText_MSG_0CF1[] = "	)	Master Knoll...\x03...Still have questions, do you?I have told you all that I know.\x03	I'm not sure you did.\x03You said that you could see...ripplesof future disasters, is that it?\x03And the greater the disaster, themore clearly you could read it?\x03Does that mean you saw something?Some tremendous disaster to come?\x03......\x03	And in knowing about the disaster,Lyon thought he could prevent it.\x03Could he have...\x03Was he studying the Sacred Stone tofind a way to prevent this disaster?\x03And what will you do, nowthat you know this, too?\x03Haven't you called suchknowledge blasphemous?\x03	I...don't know what to do.\x03If my mentor were here, I thinkhe might be able to guide me.\x03But I'm still so inexperienced.I feel lost in this dilemma.\x03......\x03	But how can I not act on this?\x03If I do nothing, knowing thatsomething terrible will happen...\x03If I could have helped...I... I don't know what to do.\x03...Within five years, half ofGrado will be destroyed.\x03	Destroyed?\x03In the southern half of the continent,there will be a terrible quake.\x03The ground will shake violently.The earth will crack open wide.\x03Cities will fall. Fields willburn in the earth's hot blood.\x03Few will survive.This is what we have foreseen.\x03	How-- How can this--\x03I advise you to leave Grado.\x03You might be able to escape the disasterif you head north to Renais or Frelia.\x03	No...I can't do that.\x03When this disaster strikes, peoplewill need help and healing.\x03If I could help them even a littleby staying behind...\x03You would willingly risk certaindeath to save a handful of people?\x03	If I died serving Grado, I wouldhave no regrets, Master Knoll.\x03Thank you for sharing this. I willmake the most of this knowledge.\x03...Spoken like a true cleric.\x03You would drop everything withouthesitation just to help others.\x03This is the difference between magesand priests. Knowledge versus sacrifice.\x03Perhaps you might allow me to joinyou when the time comes...\x03	Master Knoll?\x03If I am to honor Prince Lyon'sintentions, I cannot flee this.\x03I am not sure how best I can help,but I do not want anyone to die.\x03Not if, by my action, I can save them.\x03	I understand how you feel,Master Knoll...\x03Let our strengths be united,then, for the common good.\x03";
const char gCompressedText_MSG_0CF2[] = "	Oh, great. Perfect timing.You're a priestess, aren't you?\x03	Y-yes. I am.How may I--\x03Sorry, I'm in a bit of a hurry here. Uh,could you heal this little guy for me?\x03	Heal...who?Do you mean that kitten?\x03Yeah, what's the matter?Can't you do kittens?\x03	No, that's not it. It's just,I was a little surprised to--\x03Whatever. Doesn't matter. If youcan heal him, hop to it!\x03	Oh, yes... Sorry....\x03	There. He should be fine now.\x03Aren't you a lucky little kitty?This sweet man saved you!\x03Sweet man? Me? Heh.Lady, you don't know me.\x03But thanks for saving him.\x03	Not at all. I couldn't letthe little guy suffer.\x03The name's Cormag. I'mglad I ran into you.\x03	I'm just glad I could help.My name is Natasha.\x03Well, I owe you one forsaving the cat.\x03If you need any help, justcall out, and I'll be here.\x03	I shall remember that, Cormag.\x03";
